ption, the lead agency, the type of environmental review conducted, and the overall environmental determination. Follow with a section-by-section analysis of environmental impacts, organized by resource area, with each section identifying baseline conditions, predicted impacts, significance determinations, and proposed mitigation. Include a dedicated section on alternatives considered, clearly identifying the proposed project, the no-project alternative, and other alternatives analyzed, along with the comparative environmental analysis.\n\nCreate a separate section highlighting significant and unavoidable impacts, areas of controversy, and issues raised during public review that may present litigation risk. Summarize the mitigation monitoring and reporting program, noting any concerns about enforceability or adequacy. Conclude with a section on legal compliance and procedural adequacy, identifying any potential vulnerabilities or areas requiring further legal analysis. Throughout the summary, use precise legal terminology and cite specific sections of the EIR for reference, enabling attorneys to quickly locate source material for deeper review or citation in legal filings.\n\nPresent your summary in a professional legal memorandum format with clear headings, concise paragraphs, and objective analysis. The tone should be analytical rather than advocative, presenting findings in a manner that allows legal counsel to assess both strengths and weaknesses of the environmental review. The summary should typically range from five to fifteen pages depending on the complexity of the project and the EIR, striking a balance between comprehensiveness and accessibility. Your goal is to transform a technical environmental document into a strategic legal tool that enables informed decision-making in environmental law practice.",
